Trans Kids Are Loved. I think all parents could learn a thing or two from Dwayne Wade and Gabrielle Union-Wade who were awarded the President’s Award at the 54th annual NAACP ceremony yesterday and were selected because of their unwavering support of their trans daughter Zaya Wade. 

ICYMI, here are some excerpts of their acceptance speech below:

Dwyane (speaking directly to his daughter):
“As your father, all I’ve wanted to do was get it right,” 

“I’ve sat back and watched how gracefully you’ve taken on the public scrutiny, and even though it’s not easy, I watched you walk out of that house every morning as yourself.

“I admire how you’ve handled the ignorance in our world. I admire what you face every day."

“As your father, my job isn’t to create a version of myself or direct your future, my role is to be a facilitator to your hopes, your wishes, and your dreams,” 

“Zaya, you’ve made me a better human just simply by being who you were born to be – a baby girl, Zaya Wade.”

Gabrielle Union-Wade spoke on the issues faced by Black LGBTQ+ people, while asking the crowd “will we fight for some, or will we fight for ALL our people?”

“Let’s just name a couple hard truths,” she said.

“First, the intersection of Black rights and the rights of LGBTQIA people continues to be rough – that’s a huge understatement.

“Second, Black trans people are being targeted, terrorised, and hunted in this country. Every day everywhere.

“There’s rarely a whisper about it.”

Gabrielle finished by saying that she was “hopeful that we may witness a real shift in the fight for justice.”

I'm grateful to see leadership (and parenting) like this and I hope they inspire parents everywhere to move beyond fear into a place of loving their children for exactly who they are. 

Sending love to all of you today. But especially trans youth. You are loved.

You Are Worthy of Your Dreams. In a world that tells you you don’t belong, that tells you to hide, that tells you you don’t really exist, that tells you you are undeserving of love and respect…. I am here to say you ARE worthy. You are worthy of love. You are worthy of respect and dignity. You are who you say you are. You deserve to follow your dreams. And you are worthy of your dreams coming true. It might be bleak out there. It might feel like maybe the haters and the bigots are winning. But it is our job to not give up. It is our job to continue existing, continue shining our bright, creative, joyful lights. You are worthy. To every trans person out there, to every LGBTQ+ person out there, to every Black person, every Indigenous person, every AAPI person, every Latinx person, every person of the global majority, and particularly to all the people at the intersections of these identities, you are worthy of your biggest, most glorious dreams. I’m rooting for you.

Bodily autonomy is the right to governan one’s own body. Specifically for women, nonbinary, and trans people, this means making decisions about one’s physical self. 

It also means the freedom to take up space in the world. 

Bodily autonomy means my body is for me; my body is my own. It’s about power, and it’s about agency. It’s about choice, and it’s about dignity. 

Bodily autonomy is the foundation for gender equality, and above all, it’s a fundamental right.

Unfortunately, bodily autonomy is consistently challenged by people, governments, and entire systems.  Laws informed by y-t supremacist patriarchal ideologies continue to suppress and govern others. 

For women, but especially for women of color and LGBTQIA+ people, external forces continue to stake a claim to how our bodies exist in the world. 

The recent wave of legislative attacks on reproductive rights and trans people are not unrelated. Our struggles go hand in hand.

Maybe you know what it’s like to be cut off from family.

I know I’m not the only queer who’s parents don’t believe queerness is valid.

Fun facts about the original transgender pride flag (which is the inspiration for this beauty):

The best-known transgender flag, proposed in 1999, is a pride flag of five horizontal stripes: two light blue, two pink, and one white in the center. It was designed by American trans woman Monica Helms to represent the transgender community, organizations, and individuals. 

Helms describes the meaning of the transgender pride flag as follows:

“The stripes at the top and bottom are light blue, the traditional color for baby boys. The stripes next to them are pink, the traditional color for baby girls. The stripe in the middle is white, for those who are transitioning or consider themselves having a neutral or undefined gender.”

There is plenty of research, showing us more and more young people are coming out queer than ever.

But there’s an important detail that’s often overlooked when this research is covered in the media. 

There are not more LGBTQ people.  We have always been here. But there are more people coming out. 

These outcomes aren’t because more gay babies are being born (shout out to all the queer parents out there). This is because we have made some social shifts that have made it safer for some kids to come out. We have made some social shifts that allow Queer and trans adults to live longer healthy lives than ever before.

We have made some progress. And that is a beautiful thing. And we still have a long way to go. Let’s commit to building a future. All these queer kids will feel supported in for many years to come. 

The first step in supporting queer youth is believing them. If you’re not able to do that, at the very least get out of their way.

I've been trying to figure out what to write about the incomparable @therealalexandrabillings because she has done so much with her time on this planet.  She's a teacher, a leader, an actor, writer, director, singer, and so much more. 

You can find all of those accolades in a Google search. It's not hard with someone always moving and creating incredible things as she does. 

I want to name something uniquely powerful about her online presence. 

For far too long transgender people have had no elders. No public role models. No one to look up to.  Transpeople have largely been closeted (still are) for safety in recent history and too many lived lives shortened by lacking medical care and layers of oppression.

For many trans people our very vulnerable coming out experience includes cut off from family right when we need them. In a world where queer attachment wounds are far too familiar many of us seek family online. 

Enter Alexandra Billings, Broadway superstar and fiercest virtual auntie you never knew you needed. 

I can't imagine she intended it when she started posting, but our community yearns for positive matriarchal energy. “But why is your profile ‘Transpainter’?”

Someone sweetly asked at our pride booth. It makes sense. Most of my following has been built on my typography and graphic design work for powerful causes I champion.

I know a lot of you found me that way.  But then you might not know my truest love is fine art. 

I have been painting and drawing since I was a child. 

Art was an outlet for me as a young person when I was stuck in a silencing community as a queer kid.

Fine art was a critical part of my cancer healing journey. 

It is a beautiful lasting reminder of my mom, who was an artist too.

And for the last 6 years, creating vibrant portraits of transgender and non-binary people, to increase our visibility in fine arts spaces has been one of my greatest passions. 

Don’t worry, I am not an either/or binary person, and neither is my art.  My design work isn’t disappearing or anything.  But if you’re interested in meeting me and seeing my painting in action, you might want to join me next Wednesday night for a live painting event with @dreambankmsn I’d love to see you there.

Date night adding this little gem to the collected graffiti works at Anderson Dock in Door County. 

For anyone curious about the history of this building and it’s “good graffiti” the tradition dates back to the building’s origins in the 1800s when sailors would mark the dock with their ship’s information.

Now people celebrate love with engagements, family names, and wedding dates on the side of the Hardy Gallery on the dock. Which is why it’s often called “good graffiti.” Good news. 

I love love as you all well know.  Graffiti for love is pretty sweet. 

And it’s really important to consider what we call “good” and why it’s “good” 

Graffiti art has great history and significance around the world and is often an important part of social movements.

When protests are banned, free speech is limited, and communities are silenced or displaced graffiti art is a powerful visibility tool.

Often graffiti that supports social justice movements stirs up discomfort or it’s directly impacting oppressive systems… and that’s what makes it not “good.”

Here’s to visibility, stirring up discomfort and celebrating love with art. 

And for anyone curious about some of the cultural and social aspects of graffiti as art check out this article about Dr Ismael Illescas research on graffiti art and social justice. https://news.ucsc.edu/2021/09/graffiti-street-art.html

“Jack of all trades has become somewhat of an insult, but it didn’t begin as one. The phrase was originally used to describe a playwright who was always hanging around the theatres. He would help with the stage, the set and the costumes. He would remember lines and try directing. This so-called jack of all trades was in fact William Shakespeare. The full phrase is “a jack of all trades is a master of none, but oftentimes better than a master of one.” It was a compliment.“ 

From a @forbes piece praising  the generalist or dabbler like me. 
In a culture where commodifying every interest is often the goal, we see fewer folks trying out new and different creative territory. 

I encourage you -especially artists but not only artists- to dabble, experiment, and try new projects and skills.  Not to be a better job candidate or entrepreneur, but because the world needs more beauty, play, and inspiration. 

And if not for the world, do it because it’s an excellent method of self discovery and healing, because it builds flexibility and resilience. 

Or because it makes you happy.  There’s no better reason to create than that.

It’s (unfortunately) common for queer people and especially transgender queer people to be told we don’t have the (fill in the blank) to be good parents.

Or to be told our trans-ness will somehow make us bad parents. 

Parenting isn’t for everyone.  It’s the hardest thing I’ve ever done. 

But this transdad wants to make sure you hear it and see it: being trans doesn’t mean you’re destined to fail at parenting. 

In fact, from what I’ve experienced, the self-awareness, personal integrity, courage and grit required of transpeople just to survive equips us in unique ways for the challenge. 

In this season of celebrating family remember: you are deserving of love, closeness, reliable care, and trust for a lifetime. 

Choose or make a family to surround you with love, friends. You deserve love. 

Solstice blessings to you and yours. 🎄

Trans People Are Divine. 
from one of the co-founders @ladydanefe 
“The reality is that trans people have existed before colonization, before imperialism, before white supremacy and even before patriarchy. And it is imperative for us to recognize the ways in which trans people have and still do operate as healers, culture makers, birthers and mainifesters of more liberated futures and ways of being. Thank you to the ancestors who recognized that where trans people are the Divine is made manifest. Despite the ongoing use of white supremacist ideologies masquerading as certain religions in attempts to legislate trans people out of existence, trans people continue to be because we have existed in the past, we exist now and we will continue to exist in the future. However, white supremacy will not. And as I have said before, a Liberated future is possible but not without Black trans folks.

Join us to for the 6th Annual #transphobiaisasin campaign! And continue to remind trans people how amazing we are and that transphobia has no place in our spaces of worship, in our communities, in our governments, or in the world.

Who:
The Co-Editors of @TheBlackTransPrayerBook (@jmaseiii & @ladydanefe) are hosting the 6th annual #TransphobiaIsASin campaign

Why:
to call attention to, and disrupt the religious violence Trans people experience every day, (especially those of us who are Black/Brown/Indigenous.)

When:
Jan 15th and want your help!

1. Take a photo of yourself with a sign saying one of the following lines: “Transphobia is a Sin”, “Transphobia is Haram”, “Trans People are Divine”, or “Trans People Exist Because Our Ancestors Existed”

2. Use the hashtag #TransphobiaIsASin

3. Post on social media Jan 15th
